      <section class="mb-12">
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Cross-docking operations represent the pinnacle of logistics efficiency. Cargo arrives at a distribution hub, is sorted and consolidated, then immediately ships to final destinations with minimal storage time. The right carton boxes are critical to cross-docking success. They must enable rapid sorting, optimize load planning, and maintain product protection during swift handling across Malaysia's logistics networks.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-12">
        <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-6">Why Box Design Matters for Cross-Docking</h2>
        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Standardization Speeds Sorting & Routing</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Standardized box sizes reduce sorting time. Consistent dimensions enable automated routing systems and label scanning. Right-sized boxes minimize handling errors during rapid dock operations in high-velocity fulfillment centers across Peninsular Malaysia.</p>

        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Stackability Optimizes Truck Utilization</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Well-designed boxes stack efficiently, maximizing truck space. Poor stacking wasts 10–20% load capacity. Quality corrugated construction ensures boxes withstand stacking pressure during fast-moving cross-docking operations.</p>

        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Durability for Rapid Handling</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Cross-docking involves constant movement and rough handling. Double-wall corrugated boxes withstand impacts better than single-wall. Investment in quality boxes reduces damage claims and maintains customer satisfaction in fast-paced logistics.</p>

        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Cost Efficiency at High Volumes</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Cross-docking hubs move 1000s of boxes daily. Bulk purchasing at RM 1,000 minimums provides cost advantages. Used boxes offer 40–60% savings while maintaining quality for short warehouse dwell times.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-12">
        <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-6">Optimizing Box Inventory for Cross-Docking</h2>
        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Maintaining 3–5 Day Rolling Stock</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Unlike traditional warehouses storing weeks of inventory, cross-docking requires 3–5 days of commonly-used box sizes. Frequent small orders (RM 1,000 increments) keep supply fresh without excess inventory. Quinocycle's rapid delivery from Balakong supports this model.</p>

        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Size Mix Optimization</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Analyze shipment patterns to determine the perfect size distribution. Typically: 30% small (20x15cm), 50% medium (40x30cm), 20% large (50x40cm). Mix sizes within orders to match product diversity and route requirements.</p>

        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Just-In-Time (JIT) Box Delivery</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Partner with suppliers offering flexible delivery schedules. JIT box supply minimizes dock space needed for storage while ensuring constant availability. Quinocycle supports JIT ordering across Peninsular Malaysia.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-12 bg-primary/5 border border-primary/20 rounded-lg p-8">
        <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Cross-Docking Best Practices for Box Management</h2>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm">✓ Organize boxes on accessible racks near packing areas</li>
          <li class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm">✓ Minimize walking distance between receiving and shipping docks</li>
          <li class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm">✓ Use vertical storage to maximize warehouse footprint</li>
          <li class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm">✓ Implement FIFO (First-In-First-Out) rotation systems</li>
          <li class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm">✓ Maintain consistent box dimensions for automation compatibility</li>
          <li class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm">✓ Reorder when stock drops to 2-day supply</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-12">
        <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-6">FAQs on Cross-Docking Packaging</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <details class="group border border-outline-variant/20 rounded-lg p-4">
            <summary class="font-label font-bold text-on-surface cursor-pointer">Can automated sorting systems work with various box sizes?</summary>
            <p class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm mt-3 leading-relaxed">Modern systems handle variable sizes, but standardized dimensions speed sorting. Maintain core sizes (20x15, 40x30, 50x40cm) with limited variation for optimal automation compatibility.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="group border border-outline-variant/20 rounded-lg p-4">
            <summary class="font-label font-bold text-on-surface cursor-pointer">How do I reduce cross-docking dock space for box storage?</summary>
            <p class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm mt-3 leading-relaxed">Use vertical wall-mounted racks. Implement JIT delivery. Maintain only 3–5 days' inventory. These strategies minimize floor space while ensuring adequate box availability for rapid throughput.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="group border border-outline-variant/20 rounded-lg p-4">
            <summary class="font-label font-bold text-on-surface cursor-pointer">Should I use new or used boxes for cross-docking?</summary>
